metadata.name: Celestial Rings: Algorithmic Study #70
metadata.description:
This is an exploration to create an abstract artwork using fields and growth rings and their interaction with each other. Each of the mints can have several central rings up to 14 and the rings interact with each other to form a larger structure. The structure of the rings can be uniform or rotating, with mixed colors or mono colors. Various color palettes and canvas sizes have been used.

Open it in live view and press ’s’ to save image with high resolution.

Made with p5js.

metadata.name: De/Frag #440
metadata.description:
De/Frag is an homage to a classic algorithm in early computer art: Flood Fill. As a teenager in the late '80s, and without any literature, I spent weeks implementing a version for my very own drawing program for the Atari XL. It was the first non-trivial (to me) algorithm which made me want to learn more about data structures, the concept of recursion, divide-and-conquer...

Even though Flood Fill was available in most commercial drawing & office apps of the time, I gained a deep appreciation of the algorithm by building it from scratch myself. 30+ years later I know its aesthetic possibilities are still far from exhausted. This is an invitation for re-exploration by others too!

As with many design algorithms, my primary interest isn't even the final result, but observing the inner workings. I massively slowed down and time-sliced the process for this piece. I do recommend giving each of these unique versions some time to allow them to evolve their ever-changing patterns (Note: each piece never loops!).

metadata.name: Constance & Energy #55
metadata.description:
Abstraction is part of the artistic expressions that animate my universe. I like to work on compositions that play with materials. For this project I was inspired by the abstract painting of the 1950s. 

In my usual work, I take everyday objects and play with them. For this series, I used windows from everyday consumer packaging. When I take them out, the torn paper creates the material that reminds me of the brush strokes on the canvas. 

All the random arrangements and colours were created by code using P5.js.

6 "brush" shapes 
6 basic colours 
6 additional colours 
1 to 3 different colours in one composition


Press "Enter" to save the iteration.


See license for details.

metadata.name: Alien Symphony #32
metadata.description:
As the space traveler returns to her home planet, she brings with her a collection of tables that represent music from her interstellar trip. These tables, unknown to her, represent melody and harmony in an unknown scoring. But to the space traveler, they are a beautiful reminder of the stars she has seen and the planets she has visited.
- Dark, Light and Gold modes
- hit 's' to save a 3072x3072 px .png

metadata.name: COMPUTERS #81
metadata.description:
Generative animated painting made from pixel array computations and classic noise algorithms.

COMPUTERS is a meditation on the aesthetics of computing in all of its forms. It recalls the types of computation required to build temples, write complex texts, weave detailed textiles, and program computer games. Pixels have always existed in some form or another, before and after the screen. Every iteration of COMPUTERS suggests that computation is both contemporary and ancient.

Press 'p' or click to pause the animation.
Press 's' to capture a single frame.
Made with P5.js and GLSL. By @galoandstuff.
